 And I was getting anxious whenever I saw an unread message because I felt obligated to reply immediately.\n\nNow I check messages when I choose to. I reply in a few hours, sometimes the next day.\n\nPeople called it rude at first. Then they adjusted. Now my conversations are actually more thoughtful because neither of us is firing off half-baked replies in real time.\n\nInstant communication is a feature, not an obligation. You're allowed to be unavailable.",">":1772109287575}}},"reatedAt":{"":{":":1771590876726,">":1772109287575}}},"downvotes":{"":{":":3,">":1772109287575}},"id":{"":{":":"post-1772109287575-dfb8p4x",">":1772109287575}},"score":{"":{":":56,">":1772109287575}},"title":{"":{":":"Replying to every message instantly has ruined how people communicate",">":1772109287575}},"upvotes":{"":{":":59,">":1772109287575}}},"8545-jy84797\u001b":{"author":{"Id":{"":{":":"usr_y5z6a7b8",">":1772109288545}},"Name":{"":{":":"justhere4memes",">":1772109288545}}},"c":{"o":{"mm":{"entCount":{"":{":":17,">":1772109288545}},"unityId":{"":{":":"c-unpopularopinions",">":1772109288545}}},"ntent":{"":{":":"5am wake-ups. Cold showers. No days off. 12 habits of highly effective people. Hustle while they sleep.\n\nI consumed this stuff for two years. I optimized my mornings. I tracked my habits. I journaled, meditated, read 30 books a year, and color-coded my calendar.\n\nI was miserable.\n\nNot because the habits were bad. But because I'd internalized the idea that I was only valuable if I was optimizing. Rest became guilt. Relaxation became laziness.\n\nA lot of productivity content is just capitalism with a motivational poster slapped on it. \"Work yourself to the bone — but make it a morning routine.\"\n\nSometimes the most productive thing you can do is sit outside and do absolutely nothing.",">":1772109288545}}},"reatedAt":{"":{":":1771331676726,">":1772109288545}}},"downvotes":{"":{":":2,">":1772109288545}},"id":{"":{":":"post-1772109288545-jy84797",">":1772109288545}},"score":{"":{":":56,">":1772109288545}},"title":{"":{":":"Most \"productivity\" content is just anxiety repackaged as self-improvement","undefined":1772109288545}},"upvotes":{"":{":":58,">":1772109288545}}},"9517-zu89yc3\u001b":{"author":{"Id":{"":{":":"usr_q7r8s9t0",">":1772109289517}},"Name":{"":{":":"overthinking_at_3am",">":1772109289517}}},"c":{"o":{"mm":{"entCount":{"":{":":1,">":1772109289517}},"unityId":{"":{":":"c-workstories",">":1772109289517}}},"ntent":{"":{":":"We are a B2B SaaS company. Our average employee age is 31. Our product involves enterprise data pipelines.\n\nOur team building activity was making friendship bracelets.\n\nThe facilitator — who was extremely enthusiastic in a way that made me feel personally exhausted — told us to \"pick beads that represent your personality.\"\n\nI picked a grey bead and a black bead because those are my personality.\n\nMy manager made one for \"team synergy.\" I don't know what that means but the bracelet looked chaotic.\n\nWe had a retro scheduled for the same afternoon that got pushed because \"there wasn't enough time after the activity.\"\n\nThe retro has now been rescheduled four times. The friendship bracelet is on my desk. I feel nothing.",">":1772109289517}}},"reatedAt":{"":{":":1771936476726,">":1772109289517}}},"downvotes":{"":{":":6,">":1772109289517}},"id":{"":{":":"post-1772109289517-zu89yc3",">":1772109289517}},"score":{"":{":":28,">":1772109289517}},"title":{"":{":":"My entire team got \"voluntold\" to do a team building activity. It was making friendship bracelets.",">":1772109289517}},"upvotes":{"":{":":34,">":1772109289517}}}},"9":{"0507-8jcpjpv\u001b":{"author":{"Id":{"":{":":"usr_q7r8s9t0",">":1772109290507}},"Name":{"":{":":"overthinking_at_3am",">":1772109290507}}},"c":{"o":{"mm":{"entCount":{"":{":":12,">":1772109290507}},"unityId":{"":{":":"c-workstories",">":1772109290507}}},"ntent":{"":{":":"Three years at this company. Hundreds of meetings. I have been told we will \"circle back\" on approximately 40-50 topics.\n\nWe have circled back on zero of them.\n\nThe topics include:\n- Whether we're switching project management tools\n- The Q3 hiring plan from 2023\n- What actually happened with the Singapore client\n- Whether remote work is permanent or not\n- My raise\n\nI have started keeping a log. Not because I expect resolution. But because someday I want to stand up in a meeting and read the full list out loud.\n\nCircling back is a myth. Like work-life balance and \"quick syncs.\"",">":1772109290507}}},"reatedAt":{"":{":":1772022876726,">":1772109290507}}},"downvotes":{"":{":":6,">":1772109290507}},"id":{"":{":":"post-1772109290507-8jcpjpv",">":1772109290507}},"score":{"":{":":53,">":1772109290507}},"title":{"":{":":"The guy who always says \"let's circle back\" has never, in recorded history, circled back",">":1772109290507}},"upvotes":{"":{":":59,">":1772109290507}}},"1482-s1uoa4r\u001b":{"author":{"Id":{"":{":":"usr_a1b2c3d4",">":1772109291482}},"Name":{"":{":":"kartik_dev",">":1772109291482}}},"c":{"o":{"mm":{"entCount":{"":{":":11,">":1772109291482}},"unityId":{"":{":":"c-midnightthoughts",">":1772109291482}}},"ntent":{"":{":":"It's 1:47am and I can't sleep and I've been thinking about how much effort I put into performing okayness.\n\nSomeone asks how I am. \"Good, busy but good.\" Not because I'm good. Because it's easier than explaining.\n\nI smile in meetings. I send \"haha\" in chats. I say \"I'm just tired\" when tired isn't really the word.\n\nAnd the wild thing is everyone around me is probably doing the same thing. We're all performing fine at each other while quietly not being fine.\n\nI don't have a solution. It's almost 2am. I just think we should maybe ask each other how we actually are sometimes. And actually answer.",">":1772109291482}}},"reatedAt":{"":{":":1772109276726,">":1772109291482}}},"downvotes":{"":{":":7,">":1772109291482}},"id":{"":{":":"post-1772109291482-s1uoa4r",">":1772109291482}},"score":{"":{":":30,">":1772109291482}},"title":{"":{":":"We spend so much energy trying to seem fine that we forget to actually be fine",">":1772109291482}},"upvotes":{"":{":":37,">":1772109291482}}},"2450-br5za94\u001b":{"author":{"Id":{"":{":":"usr_e5f6g7h8",">":1772109292450}},"Name":{"":{":":"noorjahan92",">":1772109292450}}},"c":{"o":{"mm":{"entCount":{"":{":":7,">":1772109292450}},"unityId":{"":{":":"c-midnightthoughts",">":1772109292450}}},"ntent":{"":{":":"I was going through old messages tonight. From 2019. The things I said, the opinions I had, the way I talked to people — some of it made me cringe so hard I put my phone face down.\n\nBut that person was 22, figuring it out, working with the information and emotional capacity they had at the time.\n\nWe're so quick to be retrospectively ashamed of old selves. But shame doesn't retroactively give that version of you the knowledge you have now.\n\nYou grew. That's the whole point. The embarrassment means you're better now.\n\nBe a little gentler to your past self. They got you here.",">":1772109292450}}},"reatedAt":{"":{":":1771936476726,">":1772109292450}}},"downvotes":{"":{":":5,">":1772109292450}},"id":{"":{":":"post-1772109292450-br5za94",">":1772109292450}},"score":{"":{":":28,">":1772109292450}},"title":{"":{":":"The version of yourself you're embarrassed about from 5 years ago was doing their best",">":1772109292450}},"upvotes":{"":{":":33,">":1772109292450}}}}}},"08":{"54":{"2":{"6":{"023-j98rafg\u001b":{"author":{"Id":{"":{":":"usr_e5f6g7h8",">":1772085426024}},"Name":{"":{":":"noorjahan92",">":1772085426024}}},"c":{"o":{"mm":{"entCount":{"":{"undefined":9,">":1772085426024}},"unityId":{"":{":":"c-devlife",">":1772085426024}}},"ntent":{"":{":":"Not a typo. Four hours.\n\nI've been coding for 6 years. I have a CS degree. I've shipped production systems used by actual humans.\n\nAnd I spent four hours — FOUR — hunting down a bug that turned out to be a missing semicolon in a config file that nobody told me existed.\n\nThe worst part? When I found it, I didn't feel relief. I felt nothing. Just a hollow emptiness where my afternoon used to be.\n\nAnyone else ever have a bug that made you question your entire career choice? Drop it below. I need to feel less alone right now.",">":1772085426024}}},"reatedAt":{"":{":":1771826221017,">":1772085426024}}},"downvotes":{"":{":":3,">":1772085426024}},"id":{"":{":":"post-1772085426023-j98rafg",">":1772085426024}},"score":{"":{":":43,">":1772085426024}},"title":{"":{":":"Just spent 4 hours debugging. The bug was a missing semicolon.",">":1772085426024}},"upvotes":{"":{":":46,">":1772085426024}}},"994-4ovuujw\u001b":{"author":{"Id":{"":{":":"usr_i9j0k1l2",">":1772085426995}},"Name":{"":{":":"silent_debugger",">":1772085426995}}},"c":{"o":{"mm":{"entCount":{"":{":":0,">":1772085426995}},"unityId":{"":{":":"c-devlife",">":1772085426995}}},"ntent":{"":{":":"Context: I work at a mid-sized logistics company. Our flagship product is a dashboard that lets warehouse managers export reports to Excel.\n\nToday in our sprint planning, my manager — who once asked if we could \"make the database faster by using a bigger monitor\" — looked at the quarterly roadmap and said:\n\n\"I've been reading a lot about AI. Can we add AI to the Excel export?\"\n\nI asked what he meant. He said he wanted it to be \"smarter.\"\n\nI asked smarter how.\n\nHe said \"like ChatGPT but for Excel.\"\n\nI closed my laptop. I looked out the window. I thought about becoming a farmer.\n\nWe ship in 3 weeks.",">":1772085426995}}},"reatedAt":{"":{":":1771999021017,">":1772085426995}}},"downvotes":{"":{":":7,">":1772085426995}},"id":{"":{":":"post-1772085426994-4ovuujw",">":1772085426995}},"score":{"":{":":28,"undefined":1772085426995}},"title":{"":{":":"My manager just asked if we can \"add AI\" to our Excel export feature",">":1772085426995}},"upvotes":{"":{":":35,">":1772085426995}}}},"7969-zl4bm6p\u001b":{"author":{"Id":{"":{":":"usr_c9d0e1f2",">":1772085427970}},"Name":{"":{":":"literallyTired",">":1772085427970}}},"c":{"o":{"mm":{"entCount":{"":{":":3,">":1772085427970}},"unityId":{"":{":":"c-devlife",">":1772085427970}}},"ntent":{"":{":":"Every time a junior on my team shows me code, they apologize before I even look at it. \"Sorry it's a bit messy.\" \"I know this isn't ideal.\" \"I'm going to refactor this.\"\n\nWe've somehow created a culture where getting something working isn't enough — it also has to be beautiful, SOLID-compliant, fully typed, zero side effects, and ready for a tech talk.\n\nI've seen juniors spend three days refactoring code that worked fine because they were scared someone would judge it in a PR review.\n\nPerfect is the enemy of shipped. Messy code that works beats elegant code that doesn't exist.\n\nSeniors: stop roasting working code in reviews. Encourage the ship. Clean it up together later.",">":1772085427970}}},"reatedAt":{"":{":":1771480621017,">":1772085427970}}},"downvotes":{"":{":":7,">":1772085427970}},"id":{"":{":":"post-1772085427969-zl4bm6p",">":1772085427970}},"score":{"":{":":56,">":1772085427970}},"title":{"":{":":"Hot take: \"clean code\" culture has made junior devs terrified to just make things work",">":1772085427970}},"upvotes":{"":{":":63,">":1772085427970}}},"8970-0oivy15\u001b":{"author":{"Id":{"":{":":"usr_c9d0e1f2",">":1772085428970}},"Name":{"":{":":"literallyTired",">":1772085428970}}},"c":{"o":{"mm":{"entCount":{"":{":":19,">":1772085428970}},"unityId":{"":{":":"c-adulting",">":1772085428970}}},"ntent":{"":{":":"I'm 26. I have a full-time job, a small apartment, and I cook maybe 4 times a week.\n\nAnd I am EXHAUSTED.\n\nMy parents raised three kids, worked two jobs between them, maintained a house, kept the car running, remembered everyone's birthdays, and somehow still made it to my school plays.\n\nI can barely remember to buy toothpaste before I run out.\n\nI used to wonder why they never wanted to do anything on weekends. Now I spend my Saturdays lying on the couch staring at the ceiling recover